<DOC><DOCNO> AP890417-0021 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-17-89 0219EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     04-17 0496</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,430</SECOND><HEAD>Kemp Moves To Make Drug-related Evictions Easier in Federal Housing</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The federal government is making illegal druguse or sales a specific violation of public housing leases as a wayto ease the eviction process for local authorities.   Housing Secretary Jack Kemp announced the step Sunday as hereleased a report describing actions public housing authoritiesaround the country are already taking to solve drug-relatedproblems.   In a prepared statement, the secretary of Housing and UrbanDevelopment said HUD would also inform local housing authorities ofways they can use already appropriated federal funds to makephysical and management improvements aimed at improving securityagainst drug crimes.   He said HUD would publish a notice informing local housingauthorities that leases must include explicit provisions that allowtermination of the lease if any member of a household or personunder the tenant's control engages in drug-related criminalactivity.</TEXT><NOTE>___</NOTE><NOTE>Feds Help Break Up Huge Capital Cocaine Ring</NOTE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Federal and local police say they capped atwo-year investigation by breaking up a drug cartel that brought asmuch as 440 pounds of cocaine into the violence-torn Washingtonarea.   Authorities arrested about two dozen people during a weekendanti-drug sweep that netted the alleged leadership of a group thatcontrolled much of the cocaine market in the nation's capital.   Among those arrested were Rayful Edmond Jr., 24, and Tony Lewis,described as being in his mid-twenties. Officials said Sunday thatthe two led a network that controlled up to 20 percent of thecocaine and crack traffic in Washington.   The Washington Post quoted sources as saying the pair's allegeddrug network employed more than 150 people and has been linked toscores of homicides. The Post quoted sources as saying that morethan a year ago Edmond's alleged drug gang was generating income ofmore than $300,000 a day.   Edmond and Lewis were arrested Saturday on cocaine distributioncharges.   The arrests resulted from a two-year joint investigationconducted by the Drug Enforcement Administration, the FBI anddistrict police.</TEXT><NOTE>___</NOTE><NOTE>AIDS Research Funds Being Used for AZT Treatments</NOTE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Millions of dollars intended for AIDS researchis instead being used to the drug AZT for needy AIDS patientsbecause Congress reauthorized the free drug program withoutproviding money for it.   The program was to expire last September, but was extendedwithout an appropriation. Congressional leaders subsequently madeclear they expected Health and Human Services officials to tapother AIDS accounts for the money.   Although the program is authorized at $15 million for thecurrent fiscal year, the company that makes the drug _ BurroughsWellcome _ is picking up $5 million of the cost by making that muchof the drug available free.   The remaining $10 million had to be found elsewhere in the HHSbudget. About $7.4 million comes from the National Institutes ofHealth budget, and about $6 million of that from NIH research funds.</TEXT></DOC>